events.description: Alphabet reported earnings and flagged a sharp increase in AI spending for the year.
Report showing private payroll growth for January.
A session characterized by heavy selling in technology stocks and a rotation into other sectors.

facts.fact_text: S&P 500 and Nasdaq 100 futures rose on Thursday.

evidences.evidence_text: S&P 500 and Nasdaq 100 futures rose on Thursday following two straight days of heavy selling

facts.fact_text: Alphabet shares fell more than 1% in extended trading.

evidences.evidence_text: In extended trading, Google-parent Alphabet slid more than 1%

facts.fact_text: The ADP report showed private payroll growth of 22K in January.

evidences.evidence_text: ADP report showing private payroll growth slowed sharply to just 22K in January

facts.fact_text: The S&P 500 and Nasdaq Composite fell 0.51% and 1.51% respectively on Wednesday.

evidences.evidence_text: In regular trading on Wednesday, the S&P 500 and Nasdaq Composite fell 0.51% and 1.51%, respectively

claims.claim_text: Dip buyers entered the market following tech stock selling.

evidences.evidence_text: as dip buyers stepped in and as investors weighed the latest earnings results

claims.claim_text: Alphabet's increased AI spending plans supported the stock prices of Nvidia and Broadcom.

evidences.evidence_text: a move that nonetheless buoyed AI-linked names such as Nvidia (1.9%) and Broadcom (6.5%)

claims.claim_text: Investors are rotating out of the technology sector into more reasonably valued sectors.

evidences.evidence_text: as investors rotated out of tech and into more reasonably valued sectors

claims.claim_text: The ADP data indicates that labor demand is cooling.

evidences.evidence_text: reinforcing signs of cooling labor demand

evidence.evidence_text: ADP report showing private payroll growth slowed sharply... reinforcing signs of cooling labor demand
dragged down by losses in software stocks amid concerns that AI could disrupt the sector’s business models
flagging a sharp increase in AI spending this year, a move that nonetheless buoyed AI-linked names such as Nvidia
the Dow Jones rose 0.53% as investors rotated out of tech and into more reasonably valued sectors
